To everyone trashing it, is not THAT bad, what it did good, it went great, I do believe they gave it great closure, and what they did with the villain and Kylo and Rey, was very good. The movie itself was not great, far from it, but I´m glad I watched it, feel they did the best with what they had. The twists were welcome.

This trilogy lacks cohesion, that´s for sure, the first one was a good movie in my opinion, and the second and third have the same opinion about both, a few great scenes along a more or less boring movie. I don´t mind the emperor being back, actually he was better than snoke, but yes, we know it was a improvised thing. I liked the kiss, it symbolizes what would happen if shit hadn´t hit the fan, if life was easier for them. He had to die sadly, just like his grandpa. Kylo is my fav character from all the Saga, along with Han Solo, which by the way, his appearance can be explained this way: of course is not in spirit form like the jedis, but he appears thanks to KYLO, not to him! may be his subconscious or he located his spirit somehow, after all, people with the force can do all sort of amazing stuff right? :P

The emperor coming back, could´ve been amazing, they just handled it poorly for all the reasons we know (changing the director in the second movie was not a good idea). I actually like the idea that anakin died "for nothing" just like when Goku dies in DBZ against cell, and then cell comes back, was unexpected. Here they just did not made it compelling.

This is not Tarkovsky, this is entertainment, just as the original trilogy, try to enjoy it and don´t become too anal about it I´m afraid that people forget this movies are made to sell toys, I´m not a fan but always liked some good starwars fun, this one delivered, then I can go back to real film.

I somewhat disagree with you. plan to see the Rise of Skywalker again even though I do not even like the movie that much; actually, I think it SUCKED. However, I want to reward J.J. Abrams for his good works. At the same time, I have refused to pay to see Knives Out, because I want Rian Johnson's career to end. Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker on its own is a bad movie. (I bought a second ticket for Jumanji: The Next Level to see Knives Out; that is how much I despised Rian Johnson and what he did to Star Wars.) Everyone could have known the Star Wars movie that followed the Last Jedi would turn out to be a huge mess created by Rian Johnson in the Last Jedi. However, this "bad movie" did somewhat salvage the Star Wars continuity and universe from the disrespectful, horrible mess of the Last Jedi. Rian Johnson had totally destroyed the internal consistency/logic of the Star Wars characters, continuity and universe. J.J. Abram really had no easy way to continue the sage or fix the messes crapped out by Johnson in the Last Jedi. Yet, somehow, J.J. Abrams actually DID manage to fix the mess... but at the expense of a making a good, entertaining movie.

In the Rise of Skywalker, Abram had to rushed through one exposition after another to "explain away" all the horseshits and messes created by Rian Johnson. Unfortunately, all the expositions left no time for this movie to develop any character or story. The Rise of Skywalker provided an excellent explanation as to why Leia was able to wield a high-level Force power in the Last Jedi, (i.e., Mary Poppins floating in space,) and why "Mary Sue" Rey could be so powerful in the using the Force without any prior training.

In both the Force Awakens and the Last Jedi, the characterization (or the lack of) of Rey and her ridiculous power level contradicted all the previous movies and television series that had established how the Force was supposed the work. Rey's ridiculous mastery of the Force -- all without any training -- also marginalized Darth Vader who was supposed to be the "Chosen One", the single most powerful Force user in the established Star Wars history, lore and prophesies. Yet, Rey was so ridiculously overpowered that her very existence undermined Anakin, Luke, Yoda, and millions of Jedi who had come before Rey, all of them who had trained hard for many, many years before they were able to use telekinesis to move even a tiny object. After J.J. Abram left the Force Awakens, the following movie was supposed to explain how and why Rey could become so overpowered, but then Rian Johnson decided to just screw over the established Star Wars canon, lore and rules, and NOT to give any reasonable explanation to Rey's powers. Johnson threw out the basic rules that had served as the foundations of the Star Wars universe, and Star Wars universe became nothing but chaotic mess in which nothing made any more sense, nothing had consistency, and nothing had any real meaning. In that respect, the Last Jedi was actually a nihilistic movie.

Fun review. You did miss they Rey and Skywalker connection. I don't think taking the name was just about her relationship with Luke. The movie is hastily done and not enough Leia material was possible, but they tried to show that Rey and Leia had bonded. Master and student training should have been more comprehensive. As a kid I felt like Luke's Dagobah training took forever, but it set a presidence, and Rey's training with Luke in Ep 8 and then Leia in Ep 9, was too short and didn't display any new power training (they did showcase that she could just make huge boulders levitate Ep 8, but she didn't even start small? I mean Luke could barely stack some rocks).


During the Ep 9 training, they could have shown how Leia did acquire some force powers, even though she didn't complete her training. Leia could have trained Rey in force healing (like Leia's special force ability) and how to reach out to Jedi force ghosts of the past (or Luke in Ep 8 or Luke's force ghost in Ep 9 could have done this too during a training scene). Then her random force healing and all the Jedi helping reflect the force lightning at the end could have made more sense. Instead, we get a random training scene of just running and some hints towards her already established split between light and dark. Also, force healing having very little drain on Rey versus causing Ben's death was terrible. Either Rey should have passed out/gotten sick after using the power on the snake then on Kylo, or Ben shouldn't have died so easily (maybe it was his limp).


I gave it a 6.5/10 as a fun action flick set in the Star Wars universe that was scattered and had poor pacing. It was a fitting end to a declining 9 part Skywalker franchise that needed to let the past die. Ep 7 brought fans back in with a familiar story and A New Hope, Ep 8 dared to take the franchise in a completely different direction that riled up some vocal fans, and Ep 9 tried to undo many parts of Ep 8 to satisfy those fans and end the series on a hollow chest with fake deaths and escalating power creep. All in all Ep 9 sacrificed storytelling to play it safe and retcon a whole portion of the prior movie while jamming in a new story line and throwing many character arcs aside. The visuals were great and I still enjoyed the movie... you just can't recreate the magic of 1977, 1980, and 1983... hopefully Disney will stop trying and just start with good storytelling in the Star Wars universe.
